What is HugePages and when should it be enabled?
HugePages allows the Linux kernel to manage memory in much larger chunks than the default 4KB. It is critical for tuning high-performance databases (like Oracle or PostgreSQL) to reduce the overhead of page table lookups and improve memory access speed.
HugePages is a feature of the Linux kernel that allows the system to manage memory in chunks larger than the default 4KB.
By default, the CPU tracks memory using small "pages." If you have a lot of RAM (like 128GB+), tracking millions of tiny 4KB pages creates a massive "map" (Page Table) that slows down the CPU. HugePages (usually 2MB or 1GB in size) makes this map much smaller and faster to read.
Where is it used?
HugePages are primarily used in high-performance environments where applications need to access massive amounts of RAM quickly:
Databases: Oracle, PostgreSQL, MySQL (InnoDB), and MariaDB.
Virtualization: KVM/QEMU (Hypervisors) use it to give "guest" VMs faster memory access.
Big Data: SAP HANA or In-memory caches like Redis.
Java Applications: Large JVM heaps benefit from reduced garbage collection overhead.

